<DOCNO> AP880411-0002 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
israeli scientists have reported discovering 
two enzymes in leech saliva that help keep blood from clotting and 
may be used to fight blood disorders and facilitate surgery 
we found two enzymes never reported before collagenase which 
breaks down collagen and apyrase which breaks down adp adenosine 
diphosphate said meir rigbi a professor at the hebrew 
university 
he said collagen and adp induce blood cells called platelets to 
stick together the first step in blood clotting he and research 
partners miriam orevi and amiram eldor have been studying leech 
saliva for three years 
scientists have known of the fluids anticlotting qualities for 
a century three decades ago a german scientist isolated and 
identified hirudin a protein contained in leech saliva that now is 
considered the most powerful anticoagulent agent available 
progress in research was hampered because of the scarcity of 
leech saliva until a new technique was developed by by rachel 
galun a research scientist in the department of parasitology at 
hebrew university 
she prepared arginine a solution of amino acid and placed it 
over a membrane of dried calf intestine she found that leeches 
took to the solution as an alternative to blood 
after leeches drank their fill scientists squeezed them to force 
out the liquid which also contained saliva and the thirsty 
leeches went back for more 
the technique gave us two advantanges rigbi said we 
start with a much purer material and we can repeat the process 
several times 
he found several small molecules that also contribute to the 
antihemostatic process the researcher said 
it seems that the leech has a battery of components which 
inhibit platelet aggregation by a variety of agents he said 
this is the lesson we are getting it may also be a lesson for 
physicians that a certain balance of drugs is necessary in the 
treatment of patients suffering blood disorders 
rigbi said his team found another enzyme called eglin which he 
described as an inhibitor of elastase produced by white blood 
cells and is trying to identify its chemical components to 
isolate them from the saliva and reproduce them as drugs 
we have grounds to believe we will discover some unknown 
compounds he said 
the research has aroused commercial interest and eldor who is 
associated with hadassah hospital is working on practical 
applications rigbi said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

