were here for to benefit everyone in the arts 
the threestory building named the miners live theater and 
completed in 1918 by members of united mine workers local 264 was 
used for labor meetings and vaudeville shows 
the theaters past is intertwined with the regions coalmining 
history according to literature about the building the first mine 
in this town of 20000 residents 15 miles east of st louis was 
established in 1857 
the industry led to the towns growth and by 1886 a man could 
walk underground through connecting tunnels between the mines from 
one edge of the city limits to the other literature says 
mining and collinsville were almost synonymous terms 
the coalmining industry slowly started to wane however and in 
1969 miners live was sold to a private company which turned it 
into a movie house 
two years ago bloomer amusement co closed the 700seat theater 
and it sat idle until february when jean spurlock reopened it and 
decided to bring in live acts and launch a performing arts school 
