<TEXT>
for a change theres no aura of crisis 
hanging over this weeks meetings of finance officials from 151 
nations a welcome development given the doomsday scenarios which 
sprang up following the stock market collapse last october 
the delegates to the spring meeting of the international 
monetary fund and the world bank will be wrestling with the 
longstanding problems of third world debt and huge trade 
imbalances as preliminary discussions get underway today in 
washington 
but six months ago many economists were predicting that the 
finance leaders would be facing the far more troubling prospect of 
a global recession triggered by the stock market plunge 
instead the world economy is growing at a faster rate than 
expected inflation is remaining subdued and the stock markets in 
the united states and other countries have regained much of the 
ground lost last fall 
for this reason analysts arent expecting any major policy 
changes to come out of the meeting wednesday between treasury 
secretary james a baker iii and his counterparts from japan west 
germany britain france italy and canada 
baker the mastermind behind some of the reagan administrations 
most successful economic initiatives is likely to urge a 
dontrocktheboat approach that will keep things on an even keel 
through the november presidential election 
in a speech last week baker boasted that significant 
progress had been made by the united states and its allies in 
promoting economic cooperation 
the seven largest industrial nations in the free world now 
have a coordination process firmly in place he said 
this will be the first meeting of the socalled group of seven 
since last september at that time unity and international 
economic cooperation were also the watchwords 
but behindthescenes disagreements between the united states 
and west germany over interest rates became public soon after the 
meeting unnerving investors and many believe contributing to the 
oct 19 stock market collapse 
the market collapse served as a strong reminder to finance 
leaders of the dangers in disharmony and on dec 22 they pledged to 
support the dollar at its current levels they then backed that 
pledge up by intervening in currency markets the process by which 
governments buy and sell currencies to influence their value 
since early this year the dollar has stabilized and the top 
industrial countries are expected to pledge anew this week to 
support that stability 
baker is also likely to push again for the other countries to 
adopt his idea of using an index of commodity prices including 
gold as one of indicators the countries use to measure the impact 
of their policies 
but some have been skeptical wondering if the proposal might be 
the first step to moving the world back to a gold standard for 
currencies something that was abandoned in 1973 when the current 
floating exchange rates were implemented 
baker denies that saying the commodity index would merely serve 
as a useful measure of inflationary pressures 
on third world debt the finance ministers are expected to 
basically reaffirm existing strategies although they may adopt some 
new approaches aimed at cutting the trilliondollar debt burden 
