<TEXT>
the needs of fish power generation 
irrigation and recreation hang in the balance as a major drought 
parches the columbia river basin 
if current conditions continue for another three years the 
northwest power planning council says the situation could be more 
severe than the drought preceding the dust bowl of the 1930s 
the columbia winds 1243 miles from its headwaters in british 
columbia to the pacific ocean on the oregonwashington border 
millions of residents in four states rely on the columbia and the 
regions other major river the 1038milelong snake for their 
livelihoods 
federal fish and power experts say that if the drought continues 
as expected into 1989 the river system could reach the breaking 
point 
few of the columbia basins 19 major reservoirs are expected to 
refill this summer said russell george chief of reservoir 
operations for the us army corps of engineers even last year 
one of the driest on record was wet enough to fill the manmade 
lakes 
when the rivers run below normal managers representing indian 
tribes three states and the federal government must decide how to 
balance competing interests 
controlled flows guarantee safe passage during the annual fall 
and spring migrations of the salmon and steelhead prized by 
commercial recreational and indian fishermen 
the water also spins turbines that light homes and power 
businesses throughout the region in good years the power flows as 
far as southern california cutting dependence on nonrenewable 
sources of energy 
starting friday a fish migration plan developed by the 
northwest power planning council calls for the us army corps of 
engineers to flush immense volumes of water down the columbia and 
snake rivers until june 15 for the benefit of spring and summer 
chinook salmon smolt 
enough water is stored along the columbia for its young fish 
but the snakes flow will not meet this years goals according to 
peter paquet of the columbia river intertribal fish commission 
to increase survival the army corps of engineers plans to use 
trucks and barges to transport some of the young fish a move that 
could avert problems faced in the years following the 1977 drought 
when 90 percent of the smolt perished damaging subsequent fish 
runs 
the receding columbia river system will reduce hydroelectric 
power generated at a series of dams throughout the basin 
reservoirs will be 70 percent to 80 percent full this year 
according to wally gibson manager of system analysis and rates for 
the northwest power planning council the council says the 
northwests power prospects for 1989 are uncertain 
the bonneville power administration already has eliminated power 
sales to california it has bought power from sources outside the 
region for the first time in 15 years said doug faulkner chief of 
bpas operations planning branch 
for irrigators the second year of drought has brought critical 
conditions to several localities particularly the yakima basin in 
central washington 
steve wade a spokesman for the us bureau of reclamation said 
severe shortages also could occur in southern idaho harming onion 
seed and fruit crops water is less scarce in the potatogrowing 
central areas of the state he said 
recreational boaters also face problems because of low water 
levels in the reservoirs 
</TEXT>
