<DOCNO> AP880411-0167 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
scientists are looking at the neem tree of 
asia and africa as a possible source of material to prevent the 
formation of aflatoxin a naturally occurring food toxin the 
agriculture department said monday 
aflatoxin can be produced by fungi that form on some farm crops 
including corn and oilseeds laboratory tests with animals have 
shown that aflatoxin is among the most powerful cancercausing 
agents known and usda has called it a potential hazard to 
humans 
usda scientist deepak bhatnagar said that as a child in india 
his parents often put leaves of the neem tree inside containers of 
wheat to keep insects from the grain now he has found that the 
leaves also may block fungi from producing aflatoxin 
in tests at the departments agricultural research service 
center in new orleans bhatnagar made solutions containing neem 
leaves he found that the solutions didnt kill the fungi but did 
block more than 98 percent of the aflatoxin they normally would 
have produced 
the fungi that produce the toxin are aspergillus flavus and a 
parasiticus 
bhatnagar said the results were promising but preliminary 
and that greenhouse studies with cotton are now being planned 
the ornamental neem is also known as margosa and nim more than 
80 insect pests including mexican bean beetles colorado potato 
beetles tobacco budworms and carpet beetles are repelled by neem 
extracts 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

