<TEXT>
the government announced monday that it will 
immediately begin accepting applications for amnesty from illegal 
aliens who overstayed their student and tourist visas 
until further notice the immigration and naturalization service 
also said it will defer the fee for such applications and issue a 
temporary work authorization card in accordance with a court 
directive 
the action is in response to a decision by us district judge 
stanley sporkin sporkin ruled march 30 that the reagan 
administration must broaden its standard for determining whether 
illegal aliens who had overstayed tourist and student visas can 
obtain amnesty under the 1986 immigration law 
last week sporkin directed ins to accept the applications 
without the customary 185 individual filing fee 
ins regulations originally stipulated that nonimmigrant aliens 
who overstayed their tourist or student visas must demonstrate that 
any violation of their immigration status had come to the attention 
of the ins before jan 1 1982 for them to qualify for the amnesty 
program 
in a ruling on a classaction suit sporkin said the regulation 
was too restrictive and declared that congress intended the law to 
mean that any government record such as tax or social security 
documents could be used to document that an illegal alien was 
known to federal authorities as of jan 1 1982 
immigration experts say the clarifications affect at least 
50000 people 
under the 1986 immigration law illegal aliens who have been in 
the country at least since jan 1 1982 may qualify for legalized 
status a 12month application period for the amnesty program is 
due to expire may 4 
