<TEXT>
soviet and american officials marked the 25th 
anniversary of the limited test ban treaty monday by hailing it as 
a historic pact that laid the groundwork for subsequent nuclear 
arms agreements 
officials gathered at the john f kennedy library and museum to 
reminisce about the events surrounding its signing 
soviet ambassador yuri dubinin praised president kennedy who 
oversaw the us side of negotiations saying the treaty would 
not have been attained without a fresh and sober look at 
superpower rivalry by that dynamic leader 
sen edward m kennedy brother of the late president called 
the treaty a watershed event in sovietamerican relations the 
first major arms control agreement involving the superpowers 
the treaty signed july 25 1963 after 10 days of negotiations 
in moscow involving soviet us and british representatives 
banned testing of nuclear weapons in the atmosphere in outer space 
and under water 
other testing bans have been signed since but the test ban 
treaty remains the only one ratified by both superpowers 
former soviet and us participants in the negotiations agreed 
at a news conference that the treaty gave rise to a series of other 
nuclear arms pacts between the superpowers including last years 
accord to eliminate intermediaterange nuclear weapons 
mcgeorge bundy special assistant for national security affairs 
from 1961 to 1966 told reporters the signing brought a prospect 
of further and larger agreements and praised kennedy for 
ignoring us perceptions that the soviets were further advanced in 
testing 
alexei roshchkin a disarmament expert in the soviet foreign 
ministry at the time of the signing concurred 
this was a first step in postwar history a first step in 
the field of disarmamanent he said 
theodore sorensen special counsel to the president from 1961 to 
1963 and part of a small group of advisers that guided the talks 
from washington by telephone said there was a great sense of joy 
and relief when word was received at the white house that the 
treaty had been signed 
but backslapping was not the kennedy way sorensen said 
on the contrary he immediately began to worry about senate 
ratification which came in the fall intense lobbying by the 
president left only 11 democrats and eight republicans opposed 
soviet officials recalled the jubilation of their leader nikita 
khrushchev as described by former kennedy aide arthur m 
schlesinger jr in his book a thousand days 
as khrushchev and us undersecretary of state averell harriman 
strode through a kremlin park a huge crowd collected behind 
them schlesinger wrote 
according to the book khrushchev turned and asked the crowd 
weve just signed a testban treaty im going to take him to 
dinner do you think hes earned his dinner the people applauded 
and applauded 
the signing and subsequent ratification followed 336 nuclear 
explosions in the atmosphere by the united states britain and the 
soviet union over 13 years 
the agreement also was important as a tangible sign of emerging 
detente after the cuban missile crisis of october 1962 brought the 
world to the brink of nuclear war 
france and china the only other nations that openly engaged in 
nuclear weapons test programs have not agreed to the test ban but 
all french nuclear explosions have been underground since 1974 and 
china exploded its last atmospheric device in 1980 
disagreement on verification measures has held up joint 
ratification of the 1974 threshold test ban treaty and the 1976 
peaceful nuclear explosions treaty limiting test explosions to 150 
kilotons a kiloton equals the explosive force of 1000 tons of tnt 
us and soviet negotiators began a second round of talks on 
ratifying those two treaties in february and participants monday 
invoked the limited test ban treaty as an example that agreement is 
possible 
</TEXT>
