<TEXT>
the writer who is based in rome recently was a 
guest in libya and took notes for this story while waiting 
around as guests often must do 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a guest in libya and there are guests 
galore does a lot of waiting but theres always the 
entertainment of watching other guests 
recently there was the man who identified himself as arthur 
blessit from southern california 
he showed up one day pulling a wooden cross on wheels and said 
hes been doing that for the past 19 years in all parts of the 
world 
he told a libyan television crew he and his teenage son planned 
to pull the cross from tripoli through the desert to ghadames 250 
miles to the south near the borders of algeria and tunisia 
when blessit and his cross rolled out of sight heinz weifenbach 
came by the hotel lobby where other guests were waiting around 
weifenbach is the burly mustachioed west german who turned to 
col moammar gadhafi for financing for his ice hockey team back 
home and he said he was waiting to catch a plane to tobruk near 
the egyptian border to hear the libyan leader make a speech 
according to jana the official libyan news agency guests pour 
into libya all the time from all over even from indian 
reservations in the united states 
judging by jana these guests most of them members of 
official delegations dont have a spare moment theyre busy 
bringing flowers to gadhafi busy touring his barrackshome that 
was damaged in the us air attacks in 1986 busy denouncing 
imperialist aggression busy signing guestbooks 
libyan officials like to present guests with programs 
programs are sometimes a tight schedule of hospital tours factory 
visits maybe even a suddenly arranged latenight chat with the 
leader as gadhafi is known here 
but the programs follow libyan time and libyan time 
means long waits in hotel lobbies and in airport lounges some 
guests frustrated by the waiting give up and start for home only 
to be yanked back at the planes door with a promise of an 
encounter with the leader 
but they eventually find out theyve returned only for more 
waiting at the hotel and looking out over the blue mediterranean 
that doesnt sound bad the trouble is all you can do generally 
is look since its difficult to get out the hotel door 
journalist guests for example are often assigned 
assistants these usually are enthusiastic but sometimes 
sourfaced young men or women who work for the information 
ministry they seem to materialize just when the guest is about to 
slip out the door for a look around 
oh you know there might be a press conference with the 
leader my assistant tells me maybe an interview maybe very 
soon 
the guest sinks into a lobby sofa and orders another soft drink 
or tea alcohol is forbidden in gadhafis revolutionary islamic 
society 
for a change of pace from lounge lounging there is corridor 
pacing many of the pacers in hotel corridors are proponents of 
various causes and countries looking for a sympathetic ear 
visitors sometimes feel like theyre in a spy movie with guests 
approaching each other stealthily whispering messages to each 
other 
an arab man leaned toward a western woman in the hotel 
restaurant and said i have something important to tell you 
yes 
you have nice legs 
one sunny afternoon four western visitors asked their 
assistants for a car to go to sabratha site of an ancient 
grecoroman theater 45 miles west of tripoli 
yes maybe there was a car but it was broken it might be 
fixed but not for several hours and the ruins close at sunset 
the guests turned to the taxi drivers outside 
sure said one fifteen dinars about 50 
the libyan assistants appeared and said something quietly in 
arabic to the driver 
thirty dinars maybe 50 said the driver 
it was clear the assistants didnt want the guests going off 
without a program 
a few days later jana reported on the doings of an austrian 
youth delegation 
the youths went to a poultry factory and to the ruins of 
sabratha it said 
they had a program 
