<TEXT>
excellence in education set off alarms with a provocative report 
that warned of a rising tide of mediocrity in us schools the 
man behind that report terrel h bell says he never expected such 
a stir but now he fears the school reform movement has left behind 
the bottom 30 percent of americas children the poor the 
minorities the dropouts 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
th bell considered by many to be the father 
of the school reform movement views himself as a failure when it 
came to educating the most important pupil he ever faced ronald 
reagan 
three years after he quit the reagan cabinet bell frets that 
school reform didnt do a darn thing to solve the problem of 
dropouts and those who can barely read the words on their high 
school diplomas most are poor many are minorities 
were losing 30 percent to 40 percent of the rising 
generation says the former secretary of education theyre out 
of school and theyre unemployed and unemployable 
it might have been different he says if president reagan had 
taken to heart the message of the bombshell report that bell 
commissioned a nation at risk 
the national commission on excellence in education made 
headlines on april 26 1983 with its blunt warning the 
educational foundations of our society are presently being eroded 
by a rising ride of mediocrity that threatens our very future as a 
nation and a people 
reagan responded by extolling tuition tax credits and prayer in 
public schools two things that a nation a risk never touched 
upon 
but the president and his advisers soon realized that it made 
political sense to pay more attention to education reagan began 
visiting schools and speaking out about the need for tougher 
standards for students and teachers alike 
bell who had come to washington to preside over a department 
reagan had promised to abolish began traveling with the president 
on air force one and handing out flags of excellence to schools 
at white house ceremonies governors and business leaders took the 
school reform message to heart and began pouring more dollars into 
local school budgets while seeking to hold educators more 
accountable 
republican party chief frank fahrenkopf jr called bell the 
secondmost important man in this administration and in perhaps 
the ultimate compliment reagan who had sought to cut billions 
from the education budget actually proposed a modest budget 
increase in 1984 an election year 
but when that election was over bell says the white house sent 
word that reagan would try with renewed vigor to boot education out 
of his cabinet bell submitted his resignation and returned to salt 
lake city to teach at the university of utah 
now he has written a book the thirteenth man a reagan 
cabinet memoir that lays bare his struggles within the 
administration and the regrets that set in after he left it 
i tried to convince the president and his people of the bonds 
that tie together education the economy and military strength but 
notwithstanding the fact that i had been a teacher for much of my 
adult life i never succeeded in getting this lesson across to 
them bell wrote 
bell in his book made no mention of his successor william j 
bennett who has been a forceful advocate of tougher standards for 
schools and colleges and has made his own headlines with studies 
comparing us and japanese schools and proposing a core high 
school curriculum 
but bell thinks the reagan administration reponse in the second 
term has been inadequate 
bennett has very effectively used the bully pulpit bell 
said in an interview but for some reason the response hasnt 
been such as to rally the whole nation around this the fact that 
were losing a third of the whole nation to academic deficiency and 
illiteracy im not talking about bennett so much as i am about 
ronald reagan 
we missed an opportunity to fully take advantage of a nation 
at risk and all the attention on it by not giving it a high 
priority and a high profile in the second term bell says had 
the president done that the results of the reform movement would 
have been much more impressive than they are 
bell credits reagan with moving the country away from the 
drift toward the welfare state and highlighting the strength of our 
capitalist free enterprise system but bell adds he could 
have added to that by being the president who turned around and 
solved the american education system we cant say that now 
bennett asked about the bell book at a congressional hearing 
said the thirteenth man suggests bell was the only virtuous 
man in the administration and the rest were knaves and louts 
unlike bell i wont leave the job and then go write a book 
criticizing the people for whom i worked bennett said 
</TEXT>
