<TEXT>
 
birth school work death epic the godfathers 
 
for a while there it seemed like bands from england had 
forgotten how to rock and roll 
thatchers island lately has produced an overabundance of 
frothing pop and synthesizerdrenched angst now along come the 
godfathers with a sound as vaguely sinister as their name 
the godfathers combine classic 1960s rock song structures with 
the aggressive cynicism of punk frankly theyd be lost in the 
crowd if placed in either of those two eras but the current lack 
of energy makes the godfathers stand out 
the title track of birth school work death performed 
with a sneer by peter coyne puts the life stinks then you die 
bumpersticker philosophy to music in the process it sums up the 
workingclass frustrations that course through the godfathers 
music 
unfortunately cliches litter their writing and nowhere is it 
more evident than here far better is if i only had time with 
a melody that leaves a more lasting impression than the chanted 
chorus of the title cut if i only had time coyne sings id 
think of the perfect crime 
guitarists mike gibson and kris dollimore shine with a sloppy 
exuberance leading one to believe their own personal godfather is 
keith richards theyre at their best in the rockabilly stb 
and the droning lead guitar salvages the silly psychedelia of 
when am i coming down 
in sound and stance the godfathers could be british cousins to 
the georgia satellites minus the sense of humor their youthful 
energy wins them more respect than their songs at this point but 
the godfathers are worth keeping an eye on 
</TEXT>
