<TEXT>
the american public may be less willing 
than the television industry believes to embrace a highresolution 
tv system with improved picture quality clearer images and more 
brilliant color according to a study released monday 
the results of the study by the media laboratory at the 
massachusetts institute of technology contradict the accepted 
wisdom which posits that high definition tv knocks the socks 
off everyone who sees it 
the study found that to most viewers the differences between 
conventional tv and high definition tv called hdtv are subtle and 
that screens would have to be two to three times the size of sets 
found in most american living rooms to have a significant impact 
the japanese have been working on hdtv for nearly 20 years and 
are moving forward quickly they plan to give a preview of their 
system with broadcasts of this summers seoul olympics to hdtv sets 
in about 50 bigcity department stores throughout the country 
the picture on a standard television set in the united states is 
produced by a signal that scans more than 200000 dots on 525 
lines the japanese system has 1125 scanning lines 
of the 613 people who participated in the study 62 percent said 
they preferred the quality of hdtv overall 
however this indicates that hdtv is not the same kind of 
revolutionary shift in technology as experienced in the transition 
to color in the 1950s and 1960s in the united states said a 
report on the study written by w russell neuman associate 
professor at the media laboratory and released at the national 
association of broadcasters convention here 
although engineers and broadcast professionals see the 
difference immediately and stronly prefer hdtv the differences 
are more subtle to the untrained eye of the mass audience the 
report said 
hdtv is the most talked about development at this years 
convention which began saturday and ends tuesday 
broadcasters are concerned that us research efforts to develop 
an industry transmission standard for hdtv still years away in the 
united states may not be moving fast enough to head off a probable 
japanese invasion of the new technology 
hdtv is expected to be introduced by the japanese to homes in 
their country in 1990 
the japanese system requires more than the space allocated to tv 
channels on the electromagnetic spectrum in japan the hdtv system 
called hivision will be transmitted by satellite to small rooftop 
antennas avoiding the bandwidth problem that would be faced by 
overtheair broadcasting but special hdtv receivers will be 
needed to see the enhanced picture 
one of the us broadcasters greatest fears is that the 
japanese will begin exporting to the united states hdtv video 
cassette recorders and receiver sets that would not receive 
overtheair broadcast signals 
were fooling ourselves if we dont think the people in the 
video cassette cable and movie industries are going to take 
advantage of that said michael j sherlock of nbc which is 
developing a system that improves picture quality though not as 
significantly as the japanese hdtv system 
broadcasters could be put out of business or severely hurt if 
we take too long to meet the competition with an improved 
television picture he said 
but neumans report said the american public is unlikely to rush 
out to buy hdtv sets which are expected to cost upwards of 3500 
when first introduced 
the media lab study admittedly an early experiment was 
conducted in a shopping mall in danvers mass in early december 
1987 for 30 minutes a total of 613 randomly selected shoppers in 
groups of five to 20 watched a variety of programs on conventional 
and hdtv sets 
though viewers could usually see a difference in picture quality 
between the two sets and overall liked hdtv more they preferred a 
conventional picture for some of the programming the study found 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

