<TEXT>
chrysler corps planned closing of its 
kenosha auto plant would cost 209 million in welfare and 
unemployment benefits along with lost taxes for the first two 
years after the shutdown a unioncommissioned study concluded 
monday 
the analysis by the midwest center for labor research in chicago 
estimated that the plants closing would cost federal state and 
local governments a total of 38000 for each unemployed chrysler 
worker 
chrysler announced in january it plans to end auto production at 
kenosha by sept 30 resulting in the layoffs of 5500 workers 
chrysler took over the plant last year as part of its purchase of 
american motors corp 
of about the two dozen studies that weve done thats the 
highest figure weve ever come up with greg leroy mclr research 
director told a news conference at the united auto workers local 
72 headquarters 
leroy said the study which was commissioned by the union local 
was based on a previous mclr study in 1985 but used more 
comprehensive welfare and employment figures from the state 
kenosha and racine counties and the us bureau of labor statistics 
it estimated that the plants closing would result in 624 
million in unemployment compensation 545 million in lost federal 
income tax revenue 26 million in lost social security tax 
revenue 214 million in welfare expenditures and 17 million in 
lost state sales and excise tax revenue 
wisconsin gov tommy thompson has threatened to sue chrysler 
claiming the detroitbased automaker broke a promise to keep the 
plant open for five years 
chrysler officials have said they may have been overly 
optimistic when negotiating with the state for improvements and job 
training funds but have repeatedly denied making any such promise 
the study indicated that 531 percent of the kenosha workers 
would still be unemployed two years after the plants closing 
in addition the study estimated that 9796 other workers in the 
state would be dislocated by the shutdown most of those jobs would 
be in companies that supply chrysler as well as people in retail 
service and other jobs supported by the buying power of chrysler 
workers 
in an economy like this the absorbtion rate just isnt there 
if jobs arent there people arent going to get reemployed 
leroy said 
he said the figures for kenosha were higher than those in other 
communities hit by large plant shutdowns because of several 
different factors in the southeastern wisconsin economy and in the 
status of unionized chrysler workers among the differences he 
cited 
kenosha has an above average unemployment rate which has 
remained above the national average for several years 
the area is strongly dependent on employment at the plant more 
than onethird of the areas total jobs would be lost with the 
shutdown 
chrysler workers make above average salaries and wages 
29120 and have benefits that many other potential employers in 
kenosha do not have 
unionized workers in general have a harder time finding new 
employment 
leroy said the study also estimated that chrysler workers would 
experience a loss in living standards within the first two years 
with welfare and compensation benefits and new employment the 
workers average income in the second year would still decline by 
775 percent he said 
local 72 negotiator rudy kuzel said the union commissioned the 
study as a public service some people in the public perceive 
this as a problem for the workers in the plant and dont realize 
its going to cost them a lot of money also he said 
kuzel said the study would be sent to state and local officials 
to aid in negotiations with chrysler 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

