johnson amp johnson and playtex 
holdings inc have terminated negotiations aimed at selling the 
playtex family products business to johnson amp johnson the 
companies said monday 
in a news release the companies cited difficulties in 
structuring and completing the definitive agreements for the 
transaction as reasons for ending the talks 
playtex said it intended to continue operating building the 
family products business which is a major maker of tampons and 
also produces toothbrushes household gloves and disposable baby 
nursers 
the business had a highly successful year in 1987 and is off 
to a strong start in 1988 joel f smilow chairman and ceo of 
playtex holdings said in the release 
on feb 16 johnson amp johnson said it had agreed to pay 726 
million for playtex family products 
industry analysts said at the time that the addition of playtex 
family products would give the health care giant more than 30 
percent of the us tampon market of which it already has about 6 
percent with the ob brand tampon 
playtex family products is one of three operating subsidiaries 
of stamford connbased playtex holdings itself once part of bci 
holdings inc the company formed by the april 1986 leveraged 
buyout of beatrice cos 
the family products division accounts for half playtexs sales 
and 70 percent of its profits smilow said 
playtexs other two divisions are playtex jhirmack inc maker 
of hair care products and playtex apparel a leading worldwide 
manufacturer of bras girdles and pantyhose 
proceeds from the sale of the family products division would 
have gone towards paying off debt incurred in the december 1986 
leveraged buyout of playtex from bci smilow said when the proposed 
deal was announced 
smilow said in the release monday that playtex family products 
would continue its efforts to sell the jhirmack division 
